Change has been successfully rebased and submitted as 9e03140656b1d93c2f4d0f3894eee8d664eb646e
binary size impact?

When I applied the patch in its current form (std::array for topCollections and std::unordered_map for topCollectionsParents), the size of BMCWeb's binary (32-bit ARM) increased by just under 66 KB.  Is that acceptable or concerning?

There are a few things I can try to further reduce the size.

For std::array topCollections I can remove "/redfish/v1" from the start of each URI.  I could also convert this to a trie.

For the topCollectionsParents it's already been established that I can't use std::unordered_map.  That will likely be replaced by a trie or something else with a smaller footprint.

There's also the possibility of being able to represent both as a single unified trie.

> increased by just under 66 KB.  Is that acceptable or concerning?

That's totally fine, just that we need to be aware when we're adding large structures like this, and be aware that generated files in the past have potentially added 100+KB worth of size, which would make bmcweb not fit on a lot of implementations.  We do have some headspace, and in theory all of this is saved if we disable aggregation, so this is fine.

SGTM.  I ended up removing the std::unordered_map as part of an idea I outline in another comment.  With that the increase should end up being smaller.  I'll leave this open for now and revisit when the code changes and size increase are more finalized.

I no longer see an increase in binary size (32-bit ARM stripped) when applying this patch in its current form on top of the previous patch in the chain.  I checked with permutations of "ls" and "du".

Removing std::unordered_map definitely had an impact, but to me it seems odd that I don't see an increase in size.

> I no longer see an increase in binary size (32-bit ARM stripped) when applying this patch in its current form on top of the previous patch in the chain.  I checked with permutations of "ls" and "du".
> 
> Removing std::unordered_map definitely had an impact, but to me it seems odd that I don't see an increase in size.

You don't actually use the structure anywhere, so the compiler is smart enough to realize that you only ever use .size(), which is constexpr on std::array, so it's optimizing that array out.
Dang, I should've just iterating over the entire thing then

I went ahead and made the change to iterating over the entire array so that it doesn't get optimized out.  This will be removed later anyway and I have to use the std::array in some way to prevent clang errors.  Please reopen this thread if you'd prefer I don't iterate over the array.
Please see the runtime memory usage requirements in the developing guide.  This should be using a constexpr array, like we do other places.
Done

There's some collections of these that we really shouldn't aggregate in a conventional sense.  TaskService for example, likely needs special handling to present a correct async task to clients.  TelemetryService is likely similar.  Account/Session service we shouldnt aggregate at all, because they're specific to the service root (ie, an aggregator user shouldn't be able to create a session on a sub ServiceRoot, only on the service root we're working with).

This is a great start;  Lets keep iterating on it.

Ignoring Account/Session makes sense so I can remove that.  We're not currently wanting to aggregate JsonSchemas so I'll remove that as well.  Right now we just specific check for it in the code in order to ignore it.

TaskService and TelemetryService are a bit interesting because there might be some relevant information at those endpoints on the satellite, but we don't expose them via the aggregator because they are not actually collections.  I don't think it's that big of an issue since the actual collections that we aggregate are things like MetricReports and Tasks which exist downtree.

We currently don't aggregate UpdateService, but we do aggregate its FirmwareInventory and SoftwareInventory collections.  TaskService and TelemetryService are structured in the same way so we should be able to handle them the same way.
I've removed JsonSchemas, AccountService, and SessionService.  I also needed to remove Sessions since ServiceRoot can link directly to that collection and it only appears at SessionService/Sessions.

I no longer need to remove just plain Sessions.  That was getting parsed due to the previous iteration of the script which wasn't as picky about how it found a NavigationProperty.  Now we don't use iter() and we explicitly match the "Name" attribute for EntityType and ComplexType objects as part of parsing each file.

As I look at this.... this is looking like a less memory efficient version of the http router.  I wonder if we should be looking at that code as at least a model for this, or storing this as a trie?

Alternatively, should we just have the policy that we have a BMCWEB_ROUTE for every top level collection, regardless of whether the bmc implements it?

This needs more thought for long-term consequences.

> As I look at this.... this is looking like a less memory efficient version of the http router.  I wonder if we should be looking at that code as at least a model for this, or storing this as a trie?

I think trie makes more since because we only really need to know if we have a URI match.  I was originally considering a trie instead of this unordered_map, but it seemed more difficult to implement cleanly as well as more tedious to use for lookups.  The latter doesn't seem as much of a concern after completing other patches in the chain and already having to parse URIs a segment at a time.


> Alternatively, should we just have the policy that we have a BMCWEB_ROUTE for every top level collection, regardless of whether the bmc implements it?

I don't think we need to actually handle the top level collections so much as make sure there is is a link to it in the parent.  We have a generic 404 handler that allows us to attempt aggregation when a request comes for an unsupported resource or collection.  The request would be handled locally and forwarded to the satellite.  When the responses are reconciled we see that we locally returned a 404 so we'll just return the satellite response as the overall response if it's a 200.


> This needs more thought for long-term consequences.

It wouldn't be difficult to go into all parents of top level collections and add links to the unsupported collection.  It'll be a bit wonky though showing links that in most instances will return a 404 regardless of aggregation being enabled.  There are roughly 70 links to top level collections or parents of a top level collection such as /redfish/v1/CompositionService.  Exposing such a large number of 404 links does not seem very user friendly to those who need to walk the tree.

I'm also worried that we'll still have to permanently maintain these URIs going forward.  Any time a new top level collection is added to the spec then we'll have to manually go into the code and add links to it in the parent code.


My preference is probably to take the trie approach since we won't have to manually maintain anything going forward.  I think we can live with needing to query the satellites now when we query endpoints like /redfish/v1.  On the satellite side these parent URIs shouldn't require nearly as many dbus calls as what's required for handling collection requests for example.

If that is an issue then I think it would be worth making an aggregation specific cache for things like this where it'd save us needing to query a satellite for information that shouldn't change.  We'd still refresh the cache of course.  Some other use cases would be knowing what query parameters such as $expand are supported by each satellite as well as what the URI for the root Chassis is.

I have a new idea.  I think I can get away with only the array of top level collections.  For the parents of top level collections I should be able to do a separate binary search routine that uses the same array rather than the unordered_map I was generating.

For example, "/redfish/v1/UpdateService/SoftwareInventory" is an entry in the array.  That URI also tells me that "/redfish/v1" can contain a link to "/redfish/v1/UpdateService".  It also tells me that "/redfish/v1/UpdateService" can contain a link to "/redfish/v1/UpdateService/SoftwareInventory".

This will be implemented in a future patch since there is not currently one in the chain that uses the topCollectionParents unordered_map.  For now I've ripped out the portion of the script that generates the unordered_map and removed references to it.
I think this can just be removed?

That depends on if I should change it instead to something like won't get optimized out like printing every element in the array so that the array.  That'd purely be for memory consumption benchmarking as talk about in our other thread.

If the memory is not a concern now that I'm only generating a single array then I can go ahead and remove this.
Actually I can't completely remove this because then I get clang failures due to defining but not using "std::array topCollections".

Marking resolved after changing this section to iterate over the entire array.  Please refer to https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/55215/comments/8e897546_ccdc8906 if you have concerns about that approach.
With aggregation, we now technically "support" these.
Then should we keep all of the xml files as well as generate the equivalent json files?

The question of filtering out schemas in general has been posed to the community at https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/59517.

For aggregation purposes I think we need to pull in all schemas since we are not aggregating schemas and it's possible that a satellite BMC will support a resource that isn't supported by the aggregating BMC.
Reply makes sense to me.

Partial review.  Every place we're using iter() we're iterating the entire XML tree, which can lead to problems where the CSDL schema isn't obeyed, but we still parse things appropriately.  Considering that we'll likely be parsing OEM schemas, I think we need to be explit when we iterate keys at each level, and make sure they're in the right thing.  These could use xpath, but that seems like overkill.  Just a simple for loop ladder seems fine.
I've updated the script to remove the use of iter().  I also added explicit matching on the "Name" attribute for EntityType and ComplexType objects.  This will prevent creating unintended paths.
This should be Log instead of LogService
Done
I split up this commit into two to clean up the diff a bit.  Let me know if that works for you.
Yeah I think that makes sense.  I've adjusted the commit message to remove the mention of enum generation.
Nit, please explicitly declare a type (probably string_view).  Letting the compiler pick is mediocre, and leads to other issues.

One other super interesting thing that boost::url added recently is static_url

https://www.boost.org/doc/libs/1_81_0/libs/url/doc/html/url/ref/boost__urls__static_url.html

Which MIGHT be constexpr constructable?  And would give us exactly the type we want, rather than having to convert from string_view.  Food for thought, not required, but would certainly be better.

I should be able to explicitly declare a type.  I'll play around and see if static_url can be used.  static_url is supposed to be declared with a fixed buffer size so I need to see how that plays with std::array.

I tried and I don't think it's possible because boost::urls::static_url is not a literal.  Maybe there's a way I can get it to work, but I don't think it's worth it.  This array is only used in string comparisons as part of binary search so I don't see a benefit in storing the URIs as static_url rather than string_view.

I now explicitly declare this as an array of string_view.
ACK.  Thanks for looking.
Should we drop /redfish/v1 on all these?  Seems redundant.

I did that to make parsing easier.  If I remove "/redfish/v1" then I'll have to do additional checks to make sure they begin with "/redfish/v1" before then going into the search logic.

It's probably still worth doing though to save space and make the lookup quicker.  I'll give it a try.
Done

I realized that I should have removed "/redfish/v1" instead of "/redfish/v1/".  Not having the leading slash makes the lookup in the future patches much trickier to implement.  I'm going to come back and fix it.

At some point we really need to deduplicate this warning.  oh well, problem for another day.
nit, nav_name in ["JsonSchemas", "accountService"...]

Pretty sure this can't run on its own, given that the higher level script deletes the old unused schema files?
Yeah this script is really dependent on being called by update_schemas.py and realistically shouldn't be run by itself.  I'll make that change.

Pretty sure we don't need clang-format off for this file.  I don't see anything that we couldn't format correctly.
NVM.  Brain fart.
Thinking out loud for a second, I wonder if we should pre-split these, so we're not having to split them on each request?  Maybe I'm over thinking it.

If you mean break this into:
/redfish/v1/TelemetryService/LogService
/redfish/v1/TelemetryService/LogService/Entries

Then yeah you're overthinking it.  We need only top level collections in the array and /redfish/v1/TelemetryService/LogService is not one.
Lets just remove this block now,  We've proven what we need to prove, and the generated code looks correct by inspection.
I removed the for loop.  I can't completely remove it or else I get compile warnings about the topCollections not being used anywhere.

According to the schema, that data is a copy from a resource which is located elsewhere in the tree.  That means it won't be subordinate to our current path and thus don't need to parse it.
